📚How to beautify your bookshelf with wrapping paper! More details: (1) To “eyeball” it, I hold the wrapping paper sheet against the shelf and make a slight crease to size it correctly. Then, I turn the crease into a fold. It’s approximate but any tiny imperfections aren’t noticeable once your shelf is filled! (2) You can be more precise by measuring with a ruler and cutting with a paper cutter. (3) There are different “furniture safe” tapes available. If I’m decorating a shelf that I will always want to cover in wrapping paper, a tiny bit of residue over time doesn’t bother me because it will always be covered!

Jane Austen second editions ✨I learned the most fascinating literary fact while visiting Jane Austen’s home. Our tour guide explained that original editions of Jane’s books would’ve had cardboard covers. The reason regency era libraries are so stunning is because wealthy people would invite bookbinders into their homes and choose their own custom bindings! That’s why old libraries often look so beautifully cohesive with their leather bound covers 📚#enchantedbyengland #enchantedbyengland

I’ve never been a city girl…but Marylebone stole a piece of my heart 💗 It’s a wonderful mix of city excitement and charm. Flower boxes adorn nearly every storefront, there’s pastel shutters on houses, plus the famous @dauntbooks on High Street( an original Edwardian bookshop specializing in travel books). I loved every moment I was there! ✨

The Pride and Prejudice Rose Walk 💐 Over the weekend, I toured @chawtonhouse with #TheEnchantedBookClub (see my blog post about it linked in my bio!). Chawton House is a beautiful manor house in the English countryside that belonged to Jane Austen’s brother, Edward. Although Jane didn’t live in Chawton House herself, she visited her brother there and lived in the village for the last eight years of her life. While wandering the Chawton House grounds, it suddenly became very clear to me that *this* was the place that surrounded some of the most prolific storytellers of all time. Would Pride and Prejudice or The Lion, the Witch, and the Wardrobe be the treasured stories they are today without the existence of the English countryside? We will never know (thank goodness) but I can’t help but believe that the English countryside co-authored the stories we hold dear 💗#enchantedbyengland

Today I visited the stunning estate where Pride and Prejudice (2005) was filmed. It is believed that Jane Austen may have based her idea of Pemberley on Chatsworth House and written the novel while in Bakewell. If you are visiting England, Chatsworth House is a MUST. Beauty that puts me at a loss for words! 📖✨ #prideandprejudice2005 #prideandprejudice #janeausten #enchantedbyengland

C.S. Lewis lived in this charming countryside home from 1930 until his passing in 1963. It was here he discovered inspiration for and wrote The Lion, The Witch, and The Wardrobe, and the rest of the Narnia series! The Enchanted Book Club’s private tour of the home was absolutely magical. We saw where Lewis sheltered children evacuees during WWII and we even enjoyed Turkish Delights in the kitchen. I was delighted to learn that C.S. Lewis’ house is *still* a home for students! I’m so in awe of England’s dedication to preservation. I can’t wait to go back with The Enchanted Book Club in 2025 📚✨ #cslewis #narnia

Did you know that Christopher Robin was a real little boy and that Winnie-the-Pooh was inspired by his real stuffed animal? In 1921, A.A. Milne’s son, Christopher Robin Milne, received a teddy bear that became known as Winnie-the-Pooh. Soon after, more stuffed animal friends came along including Piglet, Eeyore, and Tigger. Milne wrote his beloved children’s stories about Christopher and his animals. These are now on display at The New York Public Library amongst several other literary treasures! It was such a treat to see them 🍯📚✨

Hello friends! I’m Hayley, host of The Enchanted Book Club 📚🎀 Do you remember the first time a book inspired your heart? When I was a little girl, my mother gifted me a book called Great Girl Stories. I didn’t know it then, but my life would be forever changed by the inspiration literary heroines give us.

A believer of the power of stories to bring joy to our lives, I dreamed of a way to spread that joy as far and wide as I could. That’s when I created The Enchanted Book Club, a community where readers could be enchanted by beautiful stories together, a magical place that would give women the opportunity to treat themselves to something special.

The Enchanted Book Club experience has further reinforced my belief that stories are indeed magical. Our community is filled with the kindest, warmest friends I’ve ever known. We get to talk to our favorite authors on Zoom together, have virtual tea parties, discuss beloved stories, and most of all, draw inspiration from heroines to create a beautiful life.

If you’d like to join The Enchanted Book Club, you can do so at the link in my bio (I would be thrilled for you to join us) 🩷

A little about me: I believe life feels more enchanting while in a floral dress, my heart belongs to the English countryside, my favorite book is The Guernsey Literary & Potato Peel Pie Society (amongst countless others) and I am deeply grateful for our beautiful literary community! Tell me, what’s your favorite book?
